## UPDATE : Bettensor version 0.0.5
This is our Pre-V1 update (Still in Beta, for now). We are preparing our systems for new features and have done extensive changes to how miners handle data on the backend, and *we are changing our Incentive Mechanism in preparation for prediction models.*
## New Incentive Mechanism
Validators now take lifetime profitability into account with an exponential decay over time. New predictions are always weighted highest, but a larger sample size of predictions will allow us to determine who is truly differentiated. This trails off relatively dramatically after about 9 days, since that is the maximum immunity period.
Validators also disproportionately reward the top performing miners. On a smooth curve, the top 50% of miners will receive 90% of emissions. The bottom 50% can be assumed to be contributing far less valuable data and will therefore not receive much incentive.

## Miners
Mining looks pretty much the same as it did before, but state management, updates, and database access have all been refined. Lots of the bugs around updating, database access, etc have been resolved. In V1 release, coming soon, will have the major miner feature updates that you have all been waiting for. We're going to push off V1 release until next week, to ensure we have ample time to test all the new features.

Thank you all for your continued patience! We are building as quickly as we can, and as our application gets more complex, it takes more time to get things right. And we wont be surprised if you all manage to find a whole slew of new bugs for us to work on. 

Whats coming next:
- probable hotfixes (lol)
- finishing update system for past predictions (tomorrow)
- V1 update: 2 new miner interfaces, a 200m parameter football(soccer) model, website updates

"Validators score miners on their Lifetime history. There is an exponential decay algorithm used to incentivize new predictions; old predictions decrease in value over time. The top 50% of miners receive 90% of emissions."

So miners are rewarded based on their lifetime profits? Or lifetime ROI? Also, can you explain what you mean by "new predictions vs old predictions"?

Miners are scored on lifetime profits, yes. Its a bit different than a real-world consideration because everybody gets $1000 to bet with daily, and you are incentivized to bet that daily.

This is done because we need to incentivize people to bet. Otherwise a miner could refrain from betting and outperform many miners. This is why we disproportionally favor the top miners, and will likely favor them even more in the future. (we are still a young subnet, and in 'Beta' for another ~week). 

New predictions vs old predictions are just time-based. The more recent a prediction, the more its valued in the incentive structure.

Is it lifetime profits or lifetime "earnings balance"? Can you point me to the rewards mechanism on github? I am not very technical but will try to see if I can understand it better. 

For example a miner has been registered 100 days, has wagered $1,000 each day, and has returned $100,000 (Broke Even), how would that miner be rewarded compared to a miner that has been on the network 1 day, bet $1,000, and returned $2,000 (Won $1,000)?

The calculations are defined in this module:

https://github.com/Bettensor/bettensor/blob/main/bettensor/utils/weights_functions.py

The hope is that a miner that has been around for a year will not outperform a better miner that has been around for 9 days. The lifetime calculation drops off quickly, allowing a new miner to outcompete an old miner if their predictions are better, but also allows for a larger sample size in stacking miners against each other.

I am **sure** that our method is **not** perfect, and the numbers around the calculations will adjust as we monitor performance. In the future we will also require a minimum number of predictions so that we have a larger sample size, and have even discussed methods for punishing the worst + old miners so that new miners can experience a longer immunity period (currently the max is 9 days). 

Any suggestions are welcome. We have put a lot of thought into this, and our subnet will adjust to its successes and its failures.
